<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1436,1135,2025]" lastBlockId="22.[151,1437,151,464]" lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="283" pageId="21" pageNumber="282">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,532,1927,1952]" pageId="21" pageNumber="282">Comparisons and Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Mayer" authorityYear="1974" box="[538,746,1928,1952]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Epigonidae" genus="Epigonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="21" pageNumber="282" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="robustus">
<emphasis box="[538,746,1928,1952]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="282">Epigonus robustus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a member of the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Giglioli" baseAuthorityYear="1880" box="[966,1131,1928,1952]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Epigonidae" genus="Epigonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="21" pageNumber="282" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="constanciae">
<emphasis box="[966,1131,1928,1952]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="282">E. constanciae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group by having a pungent opercular spine (
<figureCitation box="[337,441,1964,1989]" captionStart="FIGURE17" captionStartId="22.[151,250,1718,1740]" captionTargetBox="[188,1398,558,1667]" captionTargetId="figure@22.[188,1398,529,1667]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURE17.Epigonus robustus, SAIAB 38259, 1of 2 specimens,155.0 mm SL.A:lateral view;B: ventral view of symphysis of lower jaw (arrows show the nub-like structures); C: SAM 13080, holotype, standard length unknown." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1182203/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="282">Fig. 17A</figureCitation>
). The species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scott" authorityYear="1962" box="[737,856,1964,1988]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Epigonidae" genus="Epigonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="21" pageNumber="282" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="lenimen">
<emphasis box="[737,856,1964,1988]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="282">E. lenimen</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having 11 + 14 vertebra; however, it differs from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scott" authorityYear="1962" box="[151,274,2000,2024]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Epigonidae" genus="Epigonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="21" pageNumber="282" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="lenimen">
<emphasis box="[151,274,2000,2024]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="282">E. lenimen</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having two nub-like structures on the symphysis of lower jaw (vs. absent in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scott" authorityYear="1962" box="[1210,1333,2000,2024]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Epigonidae" genus="Epigonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="21" pageNumber="282" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="lenimen">
<emphasis box="[1210,1333,2000,2024]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="282">E. lenimen</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and the orbital diameter shorter than postorbital length (vs. orbital diameter longer than postorbital length in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scott" authorityYear="1962" box="[1298,1420,152,176]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Epigonidae" genus="Epigonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="22" pageNumber="283" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="lenimen">
<emphasis box="[1298,1420,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="283">E. lenimen</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). The other five species of the group in the 
<collectingRegion box="[647,738,189,212]" country="Papua New Guinea" name="Western" pageId="22" pageNumber="283">Western</collectingRegion>
Indian Ocean, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Okamoto &amp; Gon" authorityYear="2018" box="[919,1072,188,212]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Epigonidae" genus="Epigonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="22" pageNumber="283" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bispinosus">
<emphasis box="[919,1072,188,212]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="283">E. bispinosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Okamoto &amp; Gon" authorityYear="2018" box="[1089,1168,188,212]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Epigonidae" genus="Epigonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="22" pageNumber="283" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="idai">
<emphasis box="[1089,1168,188,212]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="283">E. idai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Parin &amp; Abramov" authorityYear="1986" box="[1184,1395,188,212]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Epigonidae" genus="Epigonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="22" pageNumber="283" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="marimonticolus">
<emphasis box="[1184,1395,188,212]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="283">E. marimonticolus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mayer" authorityYear="1974" class="Actinopterygii" family="Epigonidae" genus="Epigonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="22" pageNumber="283" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pectinifer">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="283">E. pectinifer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Parin &amp; Abramov" authorityYear="1986" box="[318,487,224,248]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Epigonidae" genus="Epigonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="22" pageNumber="283" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="waltersensis">
<emphasis box="[318,487,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="283">E. waltersensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, have 10 + 15 vertebrae (vs. 11 + 14 vertebrae in 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Mayer" authorityYear="1974" box="[1042,1168,224,248]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Epigonidae" genus="Epigonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="22" pageNumber="283" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="robustus">
<emphasis box="[1042,1168,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="283">E. robustus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Several years ago, the second author examined the 
<typeStatus box="[481,582,260,285]" pageId="22" pageNumber="283">holotype</typeStatus>
, or rather what of left of it (
<figureCitation box="[912,1017,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURE17" captionStartId="22.[151,250,1718,1740]" captionTargetBox="[188,1398,558,1667]" captionTargetId="figure@22.[188,1398,529,1667]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURE17.Epigonus robustus, SAIAB 38259, 1of 2 specimens,155.0 mm SL.A:lateral view;B: ventral view of symphysis of lower jaw (arrows show the nub-like structures); C: SAM 13080, holotype, standard length unknown." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1182203/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="283">Fig. 17C</figureCitation>
). The specimen was collected on 
<date pageId="22" pageNumber="283" value="1903-08-20">20 August 1903</date>
during marine surveys conducted in the period 
<date box="[826,952,296,320]" pageId="22" pageNumber="283" value="1897" valueMax="1904">1897–1904</date>
by the Pieter Faure, the Government steam trawler, under the leadership of J.D.F. Gilchrist who was then Director of the Government’s Marine Biological Survey as well as Honorary Keeper of the Department of Marine Invertebrates of the 
<collectingRegion box="[1103,1168,367,392]" country="Tanzania" name="Kusini Unguja" pageId="22" pageNumber="283">South</collectingRegion>
African Museum, 
<collectingRegion box="[1378,1436,368,392]" country="South Africa" name="Western Cape" pageId="22" pageNumber="283">Cape</collectingRegion>
Town (
<bibRefCitation box="[229,467,404,429]" pageId="22" pageNumber="283" refId="ref18961" refString="Gon, O. &amp; Skelton, P. H. (1997) A history of the fish collections of South Africa. In: Pietsch, T. W. &amp; Anderson, W. D. Jr. (Eds.), Collection Building in Ichthyology and Herpetology. American Society of Ichthyologists and Herpetologists, Special Publication No. 3, pp. 133 - 168." type="book chapter">Gon &amp; Skelton 1997</bibRefCitation>
). In addition to the parts of the fish shown in 
<figureCitation box="[977,1078,404,429]" captionStart="FIGURE17" captionStartId="22.[151,250,1718,1740]" captionTargetBox="[188,1398,558,1667]" captionTargetId="figure@22.[188,1398,529,1667]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURE17.Epigonus robustus, SAIAB 38259, 1of 2 specimens,155.0 mm SL.A:lateral view;B: ventral view of symphysis of lower jaw (arrows show the nub-like structures); C: SAM 13080, holotype, standard length unknown." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1182203/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="283">Fig. 17C</figureCitation>
, the jar of 
<accessionNumber box="[1198,1336,404,428]" httpUri="http://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/SAM13080" pageId="22" pageNumber="283">
<collectionCode box="[1198,1259,404,428]" country="South Africa" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/mhew-9czz" name="South African Museum" pageId="22" pageNumber="283">SAM</collectionCode>
13080
</accessionNumber>
contains scattered bones and scales of the specimens.
</paragraph>
